We will point out several consequences of Proposition~\ref{prop: 2,3-choos 4 col grids}. We need the following technical lemma:

\begin{lem}\label{lem: ff'}
Let $H=(V_H,E_H)$ be a graph, $S_H\subset V_H$ a stable set in $H$ and $f_H: V_H \longrightarrow \mathbb{N}$ a function. We suppose:
\begin{enumerate}
\item\label{item: lemff'1} $H$ is  $([f_H,k], S_H)$-critical for some $k\geq \max\left (\max\limits_{v\in V_H}(f_H(v)); \max\limits_{v\in S_H}(f_H(v)+1)\right )$.
\item\label{item: lemff'2} Every list assignment $L_H$ verifying the following conditions is feasible:  $\forall v\in V_H, L_H(v)\subset \{1, \ldots, k\}$, $\forall v\in V_H\setminus S_H, |L_H(v)|=f_H(v)$ and $\exists i$ such that $\forall v \in S_H, L_H(v)=\{i\}$.
\end{enumerate}
Given a graph $G=(V,E)$, $f: V \longrightarrow \mathbb{N}$, $v_0\in V$, $\max_{v\in V}(f(v))\leq k$, $f(v_0)\leq k-1$, we define $G'=(V_H\cup V, E')$ obtained by adding $H$ to $G$ and linking every vertex in $S_H$ with $v_0$ and $f': V_H\cup V \longrightarrow \mathbb{N}$, defined by $f'(v)=f_H(v)+1\ \forall v\in S_H, f'(v_0)=f(v_0)+1, f'(v) =f_H(v),\ \forall v\in V_H\setminus S_H$ and $f'(v)=f(v)\ \forall v\in V\setminus \{v_0\}$.\\
Then $G'$ is $[f',k]$-choosable if and only if $G$ is $[f,k]$-choosable.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
Note that under the hypotheses we have $\max (f')\leq k$. Suppose first that $G$ is $[f,k]$-choosable and consider an $f'$-list assignment $L'$ for $G'$. We consider two cases:

{\underline{Case 1.}} Suppose $\cap_{v\in S_H}L'(v)\neq \emptyset$. We color $S_H$ with a single color $c\in \cap_{v\in S_H}L'(v)$. Using hypothesis~\ref{item: lemff'2}, this coloring can be extended to  a feasible list coloring in $V_H$. Removing $c$ from $L'(v_0)$ or any color if $c\notin L(v_0)$, we can extend the list coloring to $V$ since $G$ is $[f,k]$-choosable.

{\underline{Case 2.}} If $\cap_{v\in S_H}L'(v)= \emptyset$, then we first consider a list coloring of $G$; let $c$ be the color of $v_0$ and remove it from lists in $S_H$. Since at least one list in $S_H$ did not change, by using the fact that $H$ is $([f_H,k], S_H)$-critical, we can find a list $k$-coloring of $V_H$ without using $c$ in $S_H$, which shows that $G'$ is $[f',k]$-choosable. 

Suppose now that 
$G'$ is $[f',k]$-choosable and consider an $f$-list assignment $L$ of $G$. Since $H$ is $([f_H,k], S_H)$-critical, there is an infeasible $f_H$-list assignment $L_H$  such that $|\cup_{v\in S_H}L_H(v)|\leq k-1$. Let $c\in \{1, \ldots, k\}$ such that $c\notin \cup_{v\in S_H}L_H(v)$; w.l.o.g.,  since $f(v_0)\leq k-1$, by performing a circular permutation on colors we can suppose that $c\notin L(v_0)$. We then add $c$ in $L_H(v), v\in S_H$ and in $L(v_0)$ to get an $f'$-list assignment $L'$ for $G'$. $G'$ being $[f',k]$-choosable, there is a feasible list coloring and by property of the assignment $L_H$, at least one element in $S_H$ gets color $c$. Consequently the list coloring of $G'$ with respect to $L'$ defines a list coloring of $G$ with respect to $L$, which concludes the proof.  
\end{proof}

\begin{prop}\label{prop: 3-choos 4 col}
$[3,4]$-CH is $\Pi_2^p$-complete in 3-colorable planar graphs of degree 7, $C_{2i+1}$-free for $i\geq 4$ and such that every odd cycle $C_5$ or $C_7$ has 2 short chords.
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}

\begin{figure}[h]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{fig-3-choos-4col.pdf}
\caption{The gadget $H$ with infeasible $f_H$-list assignment.}
\label{fig: 3-choos 4 col}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

Consider the gadget $H$ in Figure~\ref{fig: 3-choos 4 col}; it consists of two diamonds sharing a vertex of degree~2 denoted by $X$; we call $Y,Z$ the two other vertices of degree~2.
We apply Lemma~\ref{lem: ff'} to $H$ with $S_H=\{X,Y,Z\}$ and $f_H(v)= 3, v\notin S_H, f_H(X)=f_H(Y)=f_H(Z)=2$ and $k=4$. To show that $H$ is  $([f_H,4], S_H)$-critical we consider the $f_H$-list assignment in Figure~\ref{fig: 3-choos 4 col}. Color 3 does not appear in $L_H(X)\cup L_H(Y)\cup L_H(Z)$ and it is straightforward to verify that it is infeasible. Suppose now that $X$ has a 3-list while $Y$ and $Z$ have a 2-list with colors in $\{1,2,3,4\}$. Suppose, without loss of generality, that $L_H(Y)= \{1,2\}$, then at least 2 colors in $L_H(X)$ can be used in a feasible list coloring of the diamond induced by $X$ and $Y$ in $H$. The same holds between $X$ and $Z$ implying that at least one color in $L_H(X)$ can be chosen such that the other vertices in $H$ can be colored. Suppose now that $|L_H(Y)|=3$, while $|L_H(X)|=|L_H(Z)|=2$. It is possible to find a feasible list coloring of the diamond induced by  $X$ and $Z$ in $H$ and then the three last vertices of $H$ can be colored greedily, $Y$ being the last one.  It is immediate to show that, if $X,Y,Z$ are colored with the same color, this list coloring can be completed if the four last vertices of $H$ are assigned to 3-lists. So, Lemma~\ref{lem: ff'} applies.

Consider now a 
 planar bipartite graph $G$, instance of $[\{2,3\},4]$-CH and denote by $V^2, V^3$ the vertices of $G$ with lists of size 2 and 3, respectively. For every vertex in $v\in V^2$, we add a gadget $H_v$ isomorphic to $H$  and link the related vertices $X_v,Y_v,Z_v$ to $v$. Let $\tilde{G}$ be the resulting graph. $\tilde{G}$ is planar, $C_{2i+1}$-free for $i\geq 4$ and every odd cycle has 2 short chords. Using Lemma~\ref{lem: ff'} for every $v\in V^2$, we show that
$\tilde{G}$ is $[3,4]$-choosable if and only if $G$ is $[\{2,3\},4]$-choosable. Using Proposition~\ref{prop: 2,3-choos 4 col grids} we conclude the proof.
\end{proof}


As pointed out in~\cite{cogis}, every bipartite graph is $[3,4]$-choosable and moreover for $k\leq 2(\ell -1)$ every bipartite graph is $[\ell,k]$-choosable. The problem turns out to be hard in bipartite graphs with a fifth color:

\begin{prop}\label{prop: l-choos k col bip}
For every $\ell\geq 3$ and every $k\geq 2\ell-1$, $[\ell,k]$-CH is $\Pi_2^p$-complete in bipartite graphs (this holds in particular for $[3,5]$-CH). If $k<2\ell-1$, the problem is trivial in bipartite graphs.
\end{prop}
\begin{proof}
We first claim that, for any $\ell\geq 3$ and every $k\geq 2\ell-1$, the gadget $H=(B\cup W, E)=K_{\binom{2\ell-2}{\ell},\binom{2\ell-2}{\ell-1}}$ is $[\ell,2\ell-1]$-critical: suppose indeed that $\ell$-lists of $B$-vertices describe all sets of $\ell$ colors among $\{1, \ldots, 2\ell-2\}$, and $(\ell-1)$-lists of $W$-vertices describe all sets of $(\ell-1)$ colors among $\{1, \ldots, 2\ell-2\}$. Then at least $(\ell-1)$ colors are needed to color $B$-vertices and consequently at least one $W$-vertex cannot be list colored. Moreover if all $B$-vertices are assigned to $\ell$-lists with colors in $\{1, \ldots, 2\ell-1\}$, while vertices of $W$ but one are assigned to $(\ell-1)$-lists, while the last one has an $\ell$-list, 


The proof is similar to the proof of Proposition~\ref{prop: 3-choos 4 col}, using a complete bipartite graph as gadget. Note indeed that $K_{\binom{2\ell-1}{\ell},\binom{2\ell-1}{\ell-1}}$ is not $[(\ell,\ell-1),2\ell-2]$-choosable. Consider indeed a list assignment with colors in $\{1, \ldots, 2\ell-2\}$ with all possible lists of $\ell$  colors for $B$-vertices and all possible lists of $\ell-1$  colors for $W$-vertices. By choosing one color in each list of $B$ we will need at least $\ell-1$ colors since for any set $S$ of $\ell-2$ colors no color will be suitable for the vertex with list $\{1, \ldots, 2\ell-2\}\setminus S$. Consequently, for at least one vertex of the right side all colors in its list will be already used in its neighborhood. 
\end{proof}

\begin{prop}\label{prop: 3-choos 5 col planar}
$[3,5]$-CH is $\Pi_2^p$-complete in triangle-free planar graphs of maximum degree 13.
\end{prop}

\begin{proof}

\begin{figure}[h]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{fig-3-5-gen.pdf}
\caption{The gadget ${\cal G}$.}
\label{fig: 3-5-fig-gen}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

\begin{figure}[h]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.4]{fig-3-5-part.pdf}
\caption{The gadget ${\cal G}_3$ with  $f_3$-list assignment forbidding color 3 for $A$.}
\label{fig: 3-5-fig-part}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

Here, we consider the gadget ${\cal G}$ in Figure~\ref{fig: 3-5-fig-gen} with central vertex $A$, of degree 11. It is made of thee isomorphic gadgets ${\cal G}_1, {\cal G}_1, {\cal G}_3$ pairwise glued by identifying two vertices. Figure~\ref{fig: 3-5-fig-part} represents ${\cal G}_3$ with a list assignment making color 3 forbidden at vertex $A$.
${\cal G}_3$ is made of two $C_5$'s, $C^1= (A,B,C,D,E)$ and $C^2=(A,B,F,G,H)$, glued by the edge $AB$ with two other $C_5$'s, namely $C^3=(a,b,c,d,e)$ linked to $C^1$ by a matching of size 5 and $C^4=(a',b',f,g,h)$ linked to $C^2$ by a matching of size 5. We define a function $f_3: V({{\cal G}_3})\rightarrow \{2,3\}$ associating 2 to $C,E,F,H$ and 3 to all other vertices. $f_3$ can be immediately extended to $V({\cal G})$ and called $f$: ${\cal G}$ is planar and vertices on the external face are alternately associated with 2 and 3 with vertices in two different ${\cal G}_i$ associated with~2. They form a set  $S$ which corresponds to black vertices in Figure~\ref{fig: 3-5-fig-gen}.  

In what follows, we show that ${\cal G}$ is $([f,5], S)$-critical. It is straightforward to verify that with the $f_3$-list assignment for ${\cal G}_3$  in Figure~\ref{fig: 3-5-fig-part}, color 3 is forbidden for vertex $A$. Hence, by a permutation of colors we can extend this list assignment to ${\cal G}$ such that color 2 will be forbidden for $A$ (using lists in ${\cal G}_2$) as well as color 1 (using lists in ${\cal G}_1$). Figure~\ref{fig: 3-5-fig-gen} shows the related lists for vertices in $S$. 
We now need to show that changing $f(s_0)$ from 2 to 3,  for one vertex $s_0$ in $S$  and denoting by $f'$ the new function, ${\cal G}$ becomes $[f',5]$-choosable. Without loss of generality we can consider that $s_0$ is a vertex of ${\cal G}_3$ and moreover, by symmetry, that it is either $F$ or $H$. 

We first need to point out some choosability properties of a $C_5$. It is $\{2,3\}$-choosable if at least one vertex has a 3-list. If all other vertices have 2-lists, then it may happen that only one single list coloring is possible. If three consecutive vertices have their color fixed and the two other vertices have 3-lists of possible colors, then there are at least two different list colorings of the whole $C_5$. Finally, the $C_5$ is not 2-choosable but the only infeasible 2-list assignment consists of five identical 2-lists. Consider now two $C_5$'s say $C^\alpha$ and $C^\beta$ linked by a matching of size~5 (say $C^\beta$ inside $C^\alpha$), assign 3-lists to vertices in $C^\beta$ and $\{2,3\}-lists$ to vertices in $C^\alpha$. If $C^\alpha$ has two different list colorings, then it will be possible to extend it on vertices of $C^\beta$. Consider indeed a first list coloring of $C^\alpha$ that cannot be extended on $C^\beta$. Necessarily, after removing from the list of every vertex $v$ of $C^\beta$ the color of its unique neighbor in $C^\alpha$, all vertices in $C^\beta$ get the same list with two colors $c_1$ and $c_2$ that are not used in the coloring of $C^\alpha$. Since at least three different colors were needed to color $C^\alpha$, $c_1$ and $c_2$ are the only colors appearing in all 3-lists in $C^\beta$. Hence, considering the second possible list coloring of $C^\alpha$,  and removing from each list in $C^\beta$ the color of its neighbor in $C^\alpha$ (if it is in its list), at least two colors are still available for every vertex in $C^\beta$ and we cannot have five equal 2-lists. Thus, $C^\beta$ can be colored. 


Consider now  ${\cal G}_3$ with any $f_3$-list assignment $L_3$, let $L_3(A)=\{i,j,k\}$. If there is no list coloring assigning color $i$ to $A$, then we show that there is at least one list coloring with $A$ colored $j$ and one with $A$ colored $k$. Moreover in each case, the color of $E$ can be arbitrarily chosen in $L_3(E)$ provided it is compatible with the color in $A$. Indeed, after coloring $A$ with $i$, there are still at least two possibilities for coloring  $C^1$ and only one blocks the coloring of the internal $C^3$. We call $col^1$ this coloring of $C^1$. This imposes the color of $B$ and then there is only one way to color $C^2$, called $col^2$, which blocks the coloring of the internal $C^4$. Hence, choosing the color of $A$ among $\{k,j\}$ and the color of $E$, compatible with the color of $A$ leads to an alternative way to color $C^1$ and $C^2$, different from $col^1$ and $col^2$ and consequently in each case the list coloring of the whole graph ${\cal G}_3$ can be completed. 

By a similar argument, we also see that if $i\notin L_3(H)$ then there is a list coloring of ${\cal G}_3$ with $A$ colored $i$ and $E$ colored with an arbitrary color of $L_3(E)$ not equal to $i$.

We are now ready to show that ${\cal G}$ is $[f',5]$-choosable. Consider any $f'$-list assignment, choose for $A$ a color that is neither forbidden in ${\cal G}_1$ nor in ${\cal G}_2$. 

{\em {\underline{Case 1:}}} $s_0=F$. Using the previous remarks, it is then possible to extend the coloring of $A$ in a list coloring of ${\cal G}_1\cup {\cal G}_2$. We then have for ${\cal G}_3$ the color of $A, E$ and $H$ fixed. There are still at least two possibilities for coloring $C^1$ with at least one that can be extended to $C^3$. Then, even if the color of $B$ is fixed, both $F$ and $G$ having 3-lists, there are at least two possibilities for coloring $C^2$ with at least one that can be extended to $C^4$.

{\em {\underline{Case 2:}}} $s_0=H$. Remove the color of $A$ from $L'(H)$ and apply the same arguments as previously.
This concludes that ${\cal G}$ is $([f,5], S)$-critical. 

The end of the proof is now similar to the proof of Proposition~\ref{prop: 3-choos 4 col}.
Consider a 
 planar bipartite graph $G$, instance of $[\{2,3\},5]$-CH, and denote by $V^2, V^3$ the vertices of $G$ with lists of size 2 and 3, respectively. For every vertex in $v\in V^2$, we add a gadget ${\cal G}_v$ isomorphic to ${\cal G}$  and link the related vertices in $S$ to $v$. Let $\tilde{G}$ be the resulting graph. It is planar, triangle-free and of maximum degree 13. Using Lemma~\ref{lem: ff'} for every $v\in V^2$, we show that
$\tilde{G}$ is $[3,5]$-choosable if and only if $G$ is $[\{2,3\},5]$-choosable. Using Proposition~\ref{prop: 2,3-choos 4 col grids} we conclude the proof. 

\end{proof}

\begin{rmk}
In~\cite{gutner}, by using an auxiliary graph $W_2$, a triangle-free planar graph with 164 vertices which is not 3-choosable was constructed. A crucial module in this construction was the occurrence of two $C_5$'s linked by a matching. Our gadget ${\cal G}$ is based on the same module but the modules are combined in a different way in order to limit the number of colors used to $k=5$. This allows us to exhibit a triangle-free planar graph with only 148 vertices which is not $[3,5]$-choosable and hence not 3-choosable: take 3 copies of ${\cal G}$ and link a new vertex to all black vertices. 
\end{rmk}




\section{Going from $k$ to $k+1$ colors in bipartite graphs}\label{sec:kk+1} 


As already mentioned a graph is 2-choosable if and only if it is $[2,4]$-choosable  and consequently, up to the threshold value of four colors, the number of available colors does not influence 2-choosability. A natural question is whether such a threshold does exist for $\ell$-choosability with $\ell \geq 3$. A negative answer was given in~\cite{kral} where the construction of graphs which are $[\ell,k]$-choosable but not $[\ell,k+1]$-choosable is given. However the graphs constructed may contain large cliques.  In this section, we show that there even exists bipartite graphs with the same property (Theorem~\ref{th: kvsk+1}). To this purpose we denote by $P(\ell,k)$ the following property:

\begin{itemize}
\begin{em}
\item[$P(\ell,k)$] There is a bipartite graph $G$ that is $[\ell , k]$-choosable  but not $[\ell , k+1]$-choosable.
\end{em}
\end{itemize}

Results on 2-choosability state that $P(2, k)$ does not hold for any $k\geq 4$ and the aim of this section is to show, that, on the contrary,  $\forall \ell\geq 3, \forall k\geq 2\ell-2, P(\ell,k)$ holds.

Note that, for all $\ell\geq 2$, every bipartite graph is $[\ell , k]$-choosable  if $k\leq 2\ell-2$~\cite{cogis} and  moreover some bipartite graphs are not $[\ell , 2\ell-1]$-choosable. Consider indeed a complete bipartite graph $K_{p,p}$, with vertex set $A\cup B$ and $p=\binom{k}{\ell}$ for $k=2\ell-1$. Consider the $\ell$-list assignment where $\{L(a), a\in A\}$ and $\{L(b), b\in B\}$ both consist of all possible lists of $\ell$ colors chosen among the $k$ available colors. 
Consider then any choice of available colors for vertices in $A$. The number of different colors used is at least $\ell$ (remember that there are $2\ell -1= \ell + \ell-1$ colors) and consequently for at least one vertex in $B$ all available colors are used in its neighborhood. So we have the following:

\begin{lem}\label{lem:2l-2}
$\forall \ell \geq 2, P(\ell, 2\ell-2)$ holds.
\end{lem}


We will first prove by induction that $P(3, k)$ holds for every $k\geq 4$. Then we will show how to extend this for larger values of $\ell$.  This requires several lemmas given below.   

The example of 2-list assignment in Figure~\ref{fig:choco} is a well known illustration that the 
chocolate is not $[2,3]$-choosable (See e.g.~\cite{rubin}).

\begin{figure}[h]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[trim = 0mm 10mm 0mm 10mm,clip,scale=0.3]{fig-choco.pdf}
\caption{An infeasible 2-list system  for the chocolate  $G(2,3)$.}
\label{fig:choco}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

Lemma~\ref{lem: chocolate} points out that this 2-list system which we call $L_2$ is the only infeasible 2-list system  in this graph.

\begin{lem}\label{lem: chocolate}
Any infeasible 2-list system for $G(2,3)$ is isomorphic to the list in Figure~\ref{fig:choco}.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
Consider the chocolate $H$ with vertices $x_1,x_6$ of degree~3 and vertices $x_2,x_3,x_4,x_5$ of degree~2 (see Figure~\ref{fig:choco}). Considering a $C_4$ $(x_1, y,z,x_6)$ in $H$: $(y,z)=(x_2,x_4)$ or $(x_3,x_5)$). Assigning the color $a$ to $x_1$ and $b$ to $x_6$ ($a\neq b, a,b\in \{1,2,3\}$) gives an impossibility on this cycle only in the case where $L(y)=\{a,c\}$ and $L(z)=\{b,c\}$ with $\{a,b,c\}=\{1,2,3\}$. 

Consider now an infeasible 2-list system for $H$ with colors $\{1,2,3\}$. Assume w.l.o.g.  $L(x_1)=\{1,2\}$. If $3\in L(x_6)$, then  $H$ is list colorable since in this case there are three different possible colorings for the pair of vertices $(x_1,x_6)$ and the list system on cycles $(x_1, x_2,x_4,x_6)$ and $(x_1, x_3,x_5,x_6)$ can exclude at most two of them.  So we have  $L(x_6)=\{1,2\}$ and this time, to exclude the two possible colorings of $(x_1,x_6)$ (i.e. (1,2) and (2,1)) we need the lists $(\{1, 3\}, \{2,3\})$ on one cycle and  $(\{2, 3\}, \{1,3\})$ on the other one. This is the claimed list assignment and any other choice gives the same up to a permutation of colors.
\end{proof}

\begin{lem}\label{lem:unique color}
For any $k\geq 4$, suppose there is a bipartite graph $H_k$ which is $[3 , k]$-choosable  and not $[3 , k+1]$-choosable, then there is a bipartite graph $\widetilde{H}_k$ and a vertex $v_0$ of $\widetilde{H}_k$ such that:\\
(i) $\widetilde{H}_k$ is $[3 , k+1]$-choosable;\\
(ii) $\forall i\in\{1, \ldots, k+1\}$, there is a 3-list system such that $v_0$ gets color $i$ in every feasible list $(k+1)$-coloring (one can force the color of $v_0$).
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
Consider  an edge-minimal bipartite graph $H'_k=(V'_k,E'_k)$ which is $[3 , k]$-choosable and not $[3 , k+1]$-choosable: for every edge $uv$, $H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$ is $[3 , k+1]$-choosable.  Such a graph necessarily exists since a stable set is always choosable. Consider an infeasible 3-list assignment $L$ of $H'_k$ with $k+1$ colors. Note that for every edge $uv$ and every list coloring of $H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$ with the 3-list system $L$, $u$ and $v$ are necessarily of the same color and in particular $L(u)\cap L(v)\neq \emptyset$. Note also that there is an edge $uv$ such that $L(u)\neq L(v)$ (else, the assignment would be necessarily feasible since $H'_k$ is bipartite).   

If  $L(u)\cap L(v)= \{i\}$ for some edge $uv$, then taking $v_0=u$  color $i$ can be forced for $u$ and the same holds for any other color by permutation of colors in $L$; in this case we just take $\widetilde{H}_k=H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$. 

So, the only remaining case is $L(u)\cap L(v)= \{i,j\}$, say for instance $L(u)\cap L(v)= \{3,4\}$ ($k\geq 4$). We then consider the graph $H''_k=(V''_k,E''_k)$ obtained from $H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$ by adding a $G(2,3)$ with bipartition $V_1\cup V_2, |V_1|=|V_2|=3$, and joining completely  $V_1$ with $u$ and $V_2$ with $v$. We then consider two cases:\\
{\em{Case 1}}: if $H''_k$ is $[3 , k+1]$-choosable, then we take $\widetilde{H}_k=H''_k$. Vertices of $V'_k$ are assigned to the 3-list system $L$ and we can add color 4 to lists in $L_2$ (See Figure~\ref{fig:choco}) for lists of vertices in $V''_k\setminus V'_k$. By definition of $H'_k$, in $H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$, $u$ and $v$ will be assigned the same color, 3 or 4 in any feasible list coloring with $k+1$ colors. However the list system prevents $u$ and $v$ from taking both color 4 and consequently color 3 can be forced for $u=v_0$.\\
{\em{Case 2}}: if $H''_k$ is not $[3 , k+1]$-choosable, consider an infeasible 3-list system $L'$ for  $H''_k$ with $k+1$ colors. Define $L'(u)=\{a,b,c\}$ and $L'(v)=\{a',b',c'\}$. Suppose that $u$ and $v$ are assigned  color $a$  and $a'$, respectively in some list $(k+1)$-coloring of $H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$ with 3-list system $L'$, then removing $a$ ($a'$) from lists of neighbors of $u$ ($v$) in $V''_k\setminus V'_k$, respectively, leads to a infeasible 2-list assignment for $G(3,2)$ and Lemma~\ref{lem: chocolate} imposes that $u$ and $v$ are colored $a$ and $a'$, respectively, in some list $(k+1)$-coloring of  $H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$ and consequently we can take $\widetilde{H}_k=H'_k\setminus \{uv\}$ and $u=v_0$, which completes the proof.
\end{proof}


For any fixed $k\geq 5$ and $K\geq k$, we define $T_{K}$ as the caterpillar in Figure~\ref{fig:KT} with vertex set $S^K\cup R^K$, where $S^K=\{s_0, \ldots, s_{K}\}$ and $R^K=\{r_1, \ldots, r_{K-1}\}$ and edges $s_0r_1, r_ir_{i+1}, i=1, \ldots, K-2, r_{K-1}s_K$ and $s_ir_i, i=1, \ldots, K-1$.

\begin{figure}[ht]
\begin{center}
\includegraphics[scale=0.5]{fig-T.pdf}
\caption{Caterpillar $T_K$.}
\label{fig:KT}
\end{center}
\end{figure}

\begin{lem}\label{lem: T}\mbox{}\\
(i) For any 1-list assignment to $S^K$ with $k$ colors such that $L(s_0)\neq L(s_1)$ and $L(s_{K-1})\neq L(s_K)$, there is a 3-list assignment to $R^K$ with $k$ colors such that there is no feasible list coloring.\\
(ii) However, $T_K$ is $f$-choosable for any  $f$ satisfying:
\begin{itemize}
\item[] $f(s_i)=1, i\neq i_0, f(i_0)=2, i_0\in\{1, \ldots, K\}$
\item[] $f(r_j)=3, j\in\{1, \ldots, K-2\}$
\end{itemize}
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
We denote by ${\cal K}$ the set of $k$ colors.
(i) Let $c_i$ be the color of $s_i$, $i=0, \ldots, K$, we construct for each $r_i$, $i=1, \ldots, K-1$, a list $L_i$ of size~3 such that there is no feasible list coloring. By assumption $c_0\neq c_1$. Let $L_1=\{c_0, c_1, c'_1\}$ with $c'_1\in {\cal K}$, $c'1\neq c_0, c_1, c_2$ ($c'_1$ is forced in $r_1$) and $L_2=\{c'_1, c_2, c'_2\}$ with $c'_2\in {\cal K}$, $c'2\neq c'_1, c_2, c_3$ ($c'_2$ is forced in $r_2$). Then in general $L_i=\{c'_{i-1}, c_i, c'_i\}$ with $c'_i\in {\cal K}$, $c'i\neq c'_{i-1}, c_i, c_{i+1}$ ($c'_i$ is forced in $r_i$), $i=3, \ldots, K-2$ with the additional constraint when choosing $c'_{K-2}$ that $c'_{K-2}\neq c_K$, which is possible since $k\geq 5$. Then by choosing $L_{K-1}=\{c_{K-1}, c'_{K-2}, c_K\}$ ($c_K\neq c_{K-1}$ by assumption) no choice is possible for the color of vertex $r_{K-1}$. This shows that with this list assignment there is no feasible list coloring while the list $L_i$ satisfies $|L_i|=3, i=1, \ldots, K-1$. 

(ii) Now we show that if some $s_i$, say $s_{i_0}$, has a list $L(s_{i_0})$ of size 2, there is a coloring whatever the lists are with the above sizes. We consider the following order of  the vertices $v_1, \ldots, v_{2K}=s_0, \ldots, s_{i_0-1}, s_{i_0+1}, \ldots, s_K, r_1, \ldots, r_{i_0-1}, r_{K-1}, r_{K-2}, \ldots, r_{i_0}, s_{i_0}$ and apply Proposition~\ref{claim: C}.  
\end{proof}




\begin{lem}\label{lem: kk+1}
If $P(\ell, k)$ and $P(\ell+1, k)$ hold, then $P(\ell+1, k+1)$ also holds.
\end{lem}

\begin{proof}
We consider a bipartite graph $H_{\ell,k}$ that is $[\ell,k]$-choosable but not $[\ell,k+1]$-choosable and a bipartite graph
$H_{\ell+1,k}$ that is $[\ell+1, k]$-choosable but not $[\ell+1, k+1]$-choosable. Moreover we assume that $H_{\ell+1,k}$ is edge minimal with respect to this property. Then we construct a bipartite graph $H_{\ell+1,k+1}$ that is $[\ell+1, k+1]$-choosable but not $[\ell+1, k+2]$-choosable.

Take an edge $uv$ of  $H_{\ell+1,k}$ and consider $H'_{\ell+1,k}=H_{\ell+1,k} \setminus\{uv\}$, that is $[\ell+1 , k+1]$-choosable. Moreover considering an infeasible $(\ell+1)$-list assignment $L$ for $H_{\ell+1,k}$ with $k+1$ colors, $u$ and $v$ necessarily get the same color in any list coloring of  $H'_{\ell+1,k}$ with the lists $L$. Let $r=|L(u)\cap L(v)|\geq 1$.  Considering a bipartition $V^1_{\ell,k}\cup V^2_{\ell,k}$ of $H_{\ell,k}$, we construct the graph $H_{\ell+1,k+1}$ obtained from $H'_{\ell+1,k}$ by adding $r$ copies $H_{\ell,k,i}$ with bipartition $(V^1_{\ell,k,i}\cup V^2_{\ell,k,i})$, $i=1, \ldots, r$ of $H_{\ell,k}$, and connecting $u$ to  $\bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^1_{\ell,k,i}$ and $v$ to $\bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^2_{\ell,k,i}$. $H_{\ell+1,k+1}$ is bipartite since $H_{\ell+1,k}$ and $H_{\ell,k}$ are and we show that it is $[\ell+1 , k+1]$-choosable but not $[\ell+1 , k+2]$-choosable.

{\underline{$H_{\ell+1,k+1}$ is $[\ell+1 , k+1]$-choosable:}}\\
Consider an $(\ell+1)$-list assignment using $k+1$ colors for $H_{\ell+1,k+1}$. Color $H'_{\ell+1,k+1}$ and call $c(u)$ and $c(v)$ the colors of $u$ and $v$, respectively. Remove  color  $c(u)$ from lists of vertices in $\bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^1_{\ell,k,i}$ and  color  $c(v)$ from lists of vertices in $\bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^2_{\ell,k,i}$ and remove arbitrarily at most one color from lists of vertices in $\bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^1_{\ell,k,i}\cup \bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^2_{\ell,k,i}$ so as to obtain exactly $\ell$ available colors for each one of these vertices. Color with $c(u)$ all vertices of $\bigcup_{i=1, \ldots, r}V^2_{\ell,k,i}$ with $c(u)$ in their own list. Then $H_{\ell,k}$ being $\ell$-choosable  with $k$ colors, the remaining uncolored graph is $\ell$-choosable  with $k$ colors and has at most $k$ colors (all colors but $c(u)$ in its lists). So the list coloring can be extended to the entire graph $H_{\ell+1,k+1}$.

{\underline{$H_{\ell+1,k+1}$ is not $[\ell+1 , k+2]$-choosable:}}\\
Denote by $\{c_1, \ldots, c_r\}=L(u)\cap L(v)$. For every $i=1,\ldots, r$,
consider an infeasible  $\ell$-list assignment using  colors $\{1, \ldots, k+2\}\setminus \{c_i\}$  for $H_{\ell,k,i}$ and add color $c_i$ to all of its lists. We define an infeasible $(\ell+1)$-list assignment of $H_{\ell+1,k+1}$ by completing this list assignment with the list assignment $L$ for $H'_{\ell+1,k}$. Indeed, for any list coloring of $H'_{\ell+1,k}$, $u$ and $v$ have the same color $c_j\in\{c_1, \ldots, c_r\}$ and then the subgraph  $H_{\ell,k,j}$ cannot be list colored, which completes the proof.
\end{proof}

We can now prove the main result of this section:


\begin{thm}\label{th: kvsk+1}
For any  $\ell \geq 3$ and any $k\geq 2\ell-2$, there is a bipartite graph that is $[\ell, k]$-choosable but not $[\ell, k+1]$-choosable (Property $P(\ell, k)$ holds.)
\end{thm}

\begin{proof}
Using Lemmas~\ref{lem:2l-2} and \ref{lem: kk+1}, it remains only to show $P(3,k)$ for any $k\geq 4$.
We will proceed by induction on $k$. $P(3,4)$ holds from Lemma~\ref{lem:2l-2}. Let us assume $P(3,k)$ holds for a fixed $k\geq 4$ and show that $P(3,k+1)$ holds. 

From Lemma~\ref{lem:unique color}, there is a bipartite graph $\widetilde{H}_k$ which is $[3, k+1]$-choosable. Moreover there is a vertex $v_0$ such that for any $i, i=1, \ldots, k+1$, one can find 3-lists such that $v_0$ gets color $i$ in any feasible list $(k+1)$-coloring. We take $k+2$ copies of $\widetilde{H}_k$, say $\widetilde{H}_{k,1}, \ldots,\widetilde{H}_{k,k+2}$ and let $v_{0,1}, \ldots, v_{0,k+2}$ be the related copies of $v_0$. Let $K=(k+2)(k+1)/2$ be the number of pairs $(i,j)$ ($1\leq i<j\leq k+2$). We take a caterpillar $T_{K-1}$  as defined in Lemma~\ref{lem: T}. It has $K$ vertices of degree~1 which we associate with every such pair $(i,j)$; let $s_{i,j}$ be the vertex corresponding to $(i,j)$. We link every vertex   $s_{i,j}$ to $v_{0,i}$ and $v_{0,j}$. In the resulting graph called $H_{k+1}$, vertices $s_{i,j}$ have degree~3. 

One verifies that $H_{k+1}$ is $[3, k+1]$-choosable. By assumption the $k+2$ graphs $\widetilde{H}_{k,1}, \ldots,\widetilde{H}_{k,k+2}$ are $[3, k+1]$-choosable. Since we use $k+1$ colors, there are at least two vertices $v_{0,i_0}, v_{0,j_0}$ which have the same color. This means that in $L(s_{i_0,j_0})$ there are at least two available colors (we remove color $c(v_{0,i_0})=c(v_{0,j_0})$). Hence, from Lemma~\ref{lem: T}(ii), the $(k+1)$-coloring can be extended to $H_{k+1}$. 

Let us now show that $H_{k+1}$ is not $[3, k+2]$-choosable. From Lemma~\ref{lem:unique color}, one can assign 3-lists to each $\widetilde{H}_{k,i}$, $i=1, \ldots, k+2$,   using in all $k+2$ colors in such a way that in each feasible list $(k+2)$-coloring, vertex $v_{0,i}$ will get color $i$. We then have to assign 3-lists to the vertices $s_{i,j}$ in such a way that the coloring cannot be extended to the entire $T_{K-1}$.  $s_{i,j}$ is linked to $v_{0,i}$ and $v_{0,j}$ ($i\neq j$) which have different colors $c_i,c_j$, so one can choose a 3-list $L(s_{i,j})$ for each vertex $s_{i,j}$ by taking colors $c_i,c_j$ and another color which can be chosen in ${\cal K}$ as was done in the proof of Lemma~\ref{lem: T} so that the coloring cannot be extended to $H_{k+1}$. This ends the proof.
\end{proof}



\section{Conclusion}\label{sec:conclusion} 

In this paper we have pointed out that when the number $k$ of colors is limited, the situation may be very different from the case where $k$ is not specified.
There are many more questions to examine in this area. 

A first question arises with respect to  the relative complexity of $[\ell, k]$-choosability and $[\ell, k+1]$-choosability. In particular, can we say that increasing the number of colors makes the problem of deciding whether a graph is choosable easier or harder. In some cases, adding one color makes the problem harder; a trivial example is given by Proposition~\ref{prop: 3-choos 4 col}: $[3,4]$-choosability has been shown hard in a class of 3-colorable graphs, while $[3,3]$-choosability is trivial on this class. A similar situation is exhibited in Proposition~\ref{prop: l-choos k col bip} between $[3,4]$-choosability and $[3,5]$-choosability of bipartite graphs. Another situation appears in Proposition~\ref{prop: 2,3-choos 4 col grids}: the proof points out that, up to a fixed threshold on the number of colors, the complexity of the problem does not change when the number of colors increases.  However, the situation is not always that simple. Theorem~\ref{th: kvsk+1} gives examples for which increasing the number of possible colors may make the problem easier. Consider indeed the class obtained by adding to any bipartite graph a bipartite graph $H_5$ that is $[3,5]$-choosable but not $[3,6]$-choosable. This transformation does not change the $[3,5]$-choosability while making the new graph not $[3,6]$-choosable. So, using Proposition~\ref{prop: l-choos k col bip}, $[3,5]$-CH is hard on this class while $[3,6]$-CH is trivial since the answer is always negative.

Among the remaining open questions, let us mention the complexity status of $[(2,3), 4]$-CH in bipartite graphs and of $[\{2,3\}, 4]$-CH in subgrids of maximum degree 3. The status of  $[3, 4]$-CH in triangle-free planar graphs is also open to the best of our knowledge.

Another research direction would be to consider the edge choosability of graphs and to examine in particular the complexity status of list edge-coloring in specific classes of graphs when the number of colors is limited. 

